his particular sexual tastes.

56:35.492 --> 56:39.326
I'm afraid he's not been very
discriminating in his partners.

56:39.963 --> 56:43.092
Some people are extremely
worried about his exposure.

56:46.970 --> 56:50.531
I hope you two can help sort this
rather delicate matter out for us.

57:05.923 --> 57:08.491
This seems to me to be a
problem for the British.

57:08.492 --> 57:10.289
Why are we involved?

57:12.095 --> 57:14.621
The British are
a civilized people.

57:14.931 --> 57:18.698
They don't eat their own. They
have somebody do it for them.

57:20.637 --> 57:22.571
So why are you telling me?

57:23.140 --> 57:27.236
I'm giving you an opportunity to
handle it. Or somebody else will.

57:43.827 --> 57:46.228
I'm sorry
you've been brought into this.

57:48.031 --> 57:51.968
If the headmaster won't listen to
reason, you might want to tie your shoe.

57:53.470 --> 57:55.529
I'm sorry
it has to be this way.

57:56.340 --> 57:59.639
It's not something I'm happy
about having to be doing.

58:12.222 --> 58:16.750
Have you thought at all about maybe
going back to teaching again full-time?

58:17.728 --> 58:21.596
They're concerned about my
personal associations, aren't they?

58:22.132 --> 58:24.897
Cambridge boys stick together
like glue.

58:25.836 --> 58:28.430
I'm far too democratic
in my tastes for them.

58:29.473 --> 58:32.499
They like pressed trousers
and proper buttons.

58:34.211 --> 58:37.806
No. I've done all the teaching
I intend to do.

58:39.249 --> 58:40.774
I am who I am.

58:42.652 --> 58:44.314
I'll suffer that.

58:48.492 --> 58:51.723
Please. You've given
all the service that you can.

58:53.263 --> 58:55.061
It's time to retire.

58:58.101 --> 59:00.661
The good schoolboy
will be close by.

59:01.471 --> 59:03.531
He'll want to know
my response.

59:06.777 --> 59:09.803
I understand if you want
to tie your shoe.

59:12.616 --> 59:17.212
It's a dirty business, Edward. I've
been part of it for far too long.

59:37.674 --> 59:41.770
You might want to think about getting
yourself a new pair of shoes, Edward.

59:43.814 --> 59:46.146
There's a wonderful shop
in St. James'.

59:46.483 --> 59:50.818
Mr. Pettibone's.
He's bootmaker to the King.

59:51.955 --> 59:55.186
But then, I suppose we all
are in our own way, aren't we?

59:55.459 --> 59:57.256
Bootmakers to kings.

01:00:01.598 --> 01:00:03.828
Get out while you still can.

01:00:04.835 --> 01:00:06.826
While you still believe.

01:00:08.438 --> 01:00:10.600
While you still have a soul.

01:00:49.479 --> 01:00:52.312
Hello. Any of you chaps got a light?

01:01:56.446 --> 01:01:57.777
I'm sorry.

01:02:06.089 --> 01:02:07.750
He knew too much.

01:02:11.828 --> 01:02:13.319
You understand.

01:02:37.754 --> 01:02:39.722
People who really love
each other don't have secrets.

01:02:39.723 --> 01:02:41.457
You are safe here with me.

01:02:41.458 --> 01:02:43.258
It appears the word
we couldn't make out

01:02:43.259 --> 01:02:46.695
had its sound wave significantly
clipped by whoever made this tape.

01:02:46.696 --> 01:02:50.189
We restored it by amplifying specific
frequencies seen on the oscilloscope.

01:02:51.501 --> 01:02:55.062
Cochinos is Spanish for
"pigs. " Let me hear it again.

01:03:01.478 --> 01:03:05.175
And the siren noise we couldn't
pinpoint before were hiding church bells.

01:03:08.318 --> 01:03:11.520
For some reason, other noises
were added to distort the bells.

01:03:11.521 --> 01:03:14.757
In the makeup table's mirror, you
can actually make out the reflection

01:03:14.758 --> 01:03:16.191
of a church steeple,

01:03:16.192 --> 01:03:19.128
whose three belfries correspond
with the bells you hear.

01:03:21.598 --> 01:03:24.366
The volume indicates that the
church is across the street,

01:03:24.367 --> 01:03:26.700
again, possibly
on a town square.

01:03:27.203 --> 01:03:29.934
On the nightstand,
we can see a clock radio.

01:03:31.608 --> 01:03:36.102
It reads almost 10:00, which would
correspond with the church bells.

01:03:36.613 --> 01:03:39.139
I also have audio
of a ceiling fan.

01:03:40.283 --> 01:03:44.119
It's a four-blade, standard ceiling
fan. We don't know where it's from.

01:03:44.120 --> 01:03:45.781
There is something here.

01:03:46.456 --> 01:03:50.324
It could be nothing significant,
maybe a candle, a paperweight.

01:03:50.627 --> 01:03:51.994
Or it may be
something personal

01:03:51.995 --> 01:03:54.463
that we could identify
the people in the room with.

01:03:54.464 --> 01:03:57.525
We're going to wash it again,
maybe see what's there.

01:03:58.501 --> 01:04:02.037
How long
until there's some definition

01:04:02.038 --> 01:04:04.166
as to exactly where we are?

01:04:04.841 --> 01:04:07.076
We're going
as quickly as we can, sir.

01:04:17.320 --> 01:04:19.788
How are Clover and your
little boy? Good, thank you.

01:04:19.789 --> 01:04:21.553
You know, he's almost five.

01:04:22.192 --> 01:04:24.285
You made quite a name
for yourself in London.

01:04:25.662 --> 01:04:27.463
The World War is over.

01:04:27.464 --> 01:04:29.064
The war for the world
has just begun.

01:04:29.065 --> 01:04:32.367
In every liberated country, there will
be a battle between us and the Russians

01:04:32.368 --> 01:04:34.496
for their hearts and minds.

01:04:36.406 --> 01:04:39.842
Since we dropped the bomb, they're
feeling a little short between the legs.

01:04:39.843 --> 01:04:43.836
The Russians still live in the
10th century. Beets and potatoes.

01:04:44.314 --> 01:04:48.083
All that will change dramatically.
Right now, they're gobbling up territory,

01:04:48.084 --> 01:04:52.886
taking home every scientist they can
steal. In 10 years, they'll have the bomb.

01:04:53.223 --> 01:04:57.455
We have to get anyone that can be useful
to us out of Berlin before they do.

01:05:02.699 --> 01:05:04.833
Churchill was right.

01:05:04.834 --> 01:05:08.031
We shouldn't have stopped
marching until we reached Moscow.

01:05:10.707 --> 01:05:12.374
They're from Switzerland.

01:05:12.375 --> 01:05:15.504
I had them sent
with the pouch to Berlin.

01:05:16.146 --> 01:05:17.880
They're a weakness of mine.

01:05:17.881 --> 01:05:21.442
When I was a child, my mother would
always reward me with a chocolate.

01:05:23.787 --> 01:05:25.414
It's a dreadful habit.

01:05:25.922 --> 01:05:27.481
Chocolates
or seeking approval?

01:05:29.125 --> 01:05:30.456
Both.

01:05:32.695 --> 01:05:35.722
He was an officer in the Abwehr,
German Military Intelligence.

01:05:39.035 --> 01:05:43.172
He says he knows the location of certain
Nazi V-2 rocket scientists in hiding.

01:05:43.173 --> 01:05:45.073
Ask him
where he wants to go.

01:05:48.845 --> 01:05:51.513
He wants to go to Chicago.
He has relatives there.

01:05:51.514 --> 01:05:55.083
Tell him if he provides us with the
names and locations of the scientists,

01:05:55.084 --> 01:05:57.485
I'll arrange
an exit visa for him.

01:05:57.921 --> 01:06:01.288
As soon as he's served his purpose,
turn him over to the Nazi catchers.

01:06:11.868 --> 01:06:16.396
An ex-Waffen-SS Group Commander would
like to speak with you about asylum.

01:06:21.211 --> 01:06:22.701
It's very ugly, isn't it?

01:06:22.979 --> 01:06:24.970
It isn't meant to be jewelry.

01:06:26.649 --> 01:06:29.141
I lost the sound
in one ear altogether.

01:06:29.485 --> 01:06:33.222
I can hear with the help of
the apparatus out of this ear,

01:06:33.223 --> 01:06:34.490
but they say
in one year or so...

01:06:34.491 --> 01:06:36.254
You hardly notice it's there.

01:06:43.333 --> 01:06:46.792
The Russians are interested
in making a prisoner swap.

01:07:11.794 --> 01:07:16.598
We are prepared to offer you some
Jewish scientists liberated in the East

01:07:16.599 --> 01:07:19.626
for some Nazi scientists
you have here in Berlin.

01:07:28.578 --> 01:07:30.910
These are the names
we're willing to discuss.

01:08:06.282 --> 01:08:10.117
I understand your cryptonym
for me is Ulysses.

01:08:11.120 --> 01:08:14.579
Is that for the James Joyce
book or the Greek myth?

01:08:20.796 --> 01:08:23.527
Do you know
what our code name is for you?

01:08:27.870 --> 01:08:29.202
Mother.

01:08:32.942 --> 01:08:37.145
I took the first hot bath
yesterday I've taken in three years,

01:08:37.145 --> 01:08:39.809
since the siege of Stalingrad.

01:08:41.551 --> 01:08:43.542
I sat for hours,

01:08:44.487 --> 01:08:46.386
looking out the window,

01:08:47.323 --> 01:08:48.984
soaking.

01:09:02.104 --> 01:09:05.598
When I was a soldier,
my fingers were frostbitten.

01:09:06.943 --> 01:09:09.435
Since then,
when I get cold,

01:09:10.279 --> 01:09:11.906
there is a pain.

01:09:14.984 --> 01:09:17.317
Maybe you shouldn't live
in Russia.

01:09:19.421 --> 01:09:21.550
We all have our weaknesses.

01:09:23.593 --> 01:09:24.924
What is yours?

01:09:28.264 --> 01:09:30.596
I had heard you were silent.

01:09:31.868 --> 01:09:34.029
"Made of stone," they said.

01:09:35.171 --> 01:09:40.041
What is the expression?
"The silence is deafening. "

01:09:44.247 --> 01:09:48.684
You are going to be a
formidable adversary, Mother.

01:09:58.361 --> 01:10:00.830
I look forward
to our association.

01:10:02.865 --> 01:10:05.232
I hope it lasts
for a long time.

01:10:21.451 --> 01:10:22.577
I love you.

01:10:23.953 --> 01:10:26.854
People who really love
each other don't have secrets.

01:10:27.757 --> 01:10:29.658
You are safe here with me.

01:10:29.659 --> 01:10:31.860
We were able to make
out the brand of the fan.

01:10:31.861 --> 01:10:34.796
It's called a Froid.
It's Belgian.

01:10:34.797 --> 01:10:39.394
The object on the nightstand, we're
still trying to find out what this is.

01:10:40.703 --> 01:10:42.501
We just can't get
any more definition out of it.

01:10:48.344 --> 01:10:50.005
Who is this?

01:10:51.347 --> 01:10:53.008
Who's this?

01:10:54.050 --> 01:10:57.076
Hello, Father. You have
a birthday coming up.

01:10:57.386 --> 01:10:58.786
I'm going to be five soon.

01:11:00.156 --> 01:11:01.749
You're a big boy.

01:11:02.825 --> 01:11:05.454
I'm bigger than Andrew,
and he's six.

01:11:09.599 --> 01:11:12.693
Is your mother there?
What? I can't hear you.

01:11:15.204 --> 01:11:17.104
Is your mother there?

01:11:17.573 --> 01:11:20.008
She's getting dressed
to go out with her friend.

01:11:20.009 --> 01:11:22.569
He has a new car.
He let me drive with him.

01:11:25.515 --> 01:11:27.278
Hello, Mr. Wilson.
This is Edna.

01:11:27.650 --> 01:11:30.552
Mrs. Wilson is upstairs.
She's getting ready for dinner.

01:11:30.553 --> 01:11:32.419
I'll tell her
you're on the phone.

01:11:34.891 --> 01:11:36.381
I'll call back.

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:45.160
Pardon me.

01:11:46.636 --> 01:11:49.867
Do you need me for anything
else? No, thank you.

01:11:58.981 --> 01:12:00.745
Do you ever eat, Mr. Carlson?

01:12:01.818 --> 01:12:05.310
I like to cook. Would you like
a home-cooked meal?

01:12:13.963 --> 01:12:17.126
Have you ever read Ovid?
Metamorphoses in the original Latin?

01:12:18.501 --> 01:12:19.991
It's quite beautiful.

01:12:23.706 --> 01:12:27.165
"I grabbed a pile of dust
and, holding it up,

01:12:27.677 --> 01:12:31.443
"foolishly asked for as many
birthdays as the grains of dust.

01:12:31.914 --> 01:12:34.816
"I forgot to ask that
they be years of youth. "

01:12:36.219 --> 01:12:37.550
Bravo.

01:12:51.234 --> 01:12:52.826
I should be going.

01:13:00.910 --> 01:13:02.469
Would you like to stay?

01:13:05.748 --> 01:13:07.409
Would you like me to?

01:13:08.951 --> 01:13:11.113
I would like you to
very much.

01:13:20.496 --> 01:13:23.198
Maybe we could go
somewhere together?

01:13:23.199 --> 01:13:25.292
The lakes in Bavaria
are still beautiful.

01:13:26.636 --> 01:13:30.971
There was an inn there before the war
where they served breakfast in bed all day.

01:13:55.464 --> 01:13:56.659
Hanna?

01:13:59.969 --> 01:14:01.903
I hope
you never go home.

01:14:04.240 --> 01:14:06.732
Bavaria is really
a beautiful place.

01:14:08.411 --> 01:14:12.404
I was born there.
My grandmother lived there.

01:14:13.816 --> 01:14:15.477
I really miss her.

01:14:17.253 --> 01:14:18.880
Why don't we go?

01:14:34.103 --> 01:14:36.470
I let a stranger
into our house.

01:15:46.742 --> 01:15:50.042
Mother! Father's here! Mother!

01:15:57.186 --> 01:15:58.517
Hello, Edward.

01:16:00.222 --> 01:16:01.713
Hello, Clover.

01:16:04.860 --> 01:16:05.850
I...

01:16:08.230 --> 01:16:10.665
I like to be called
Margaret now.

01:16:14.069 --> 01:16:16.129
It's very nice to see you.

01:16:17.773 --> 01:16:19.503
It's good to see you, too.

01:16:22.912 --> 01:16:24.743
I made something for you.

01:16:28.851 --> 01:16:31.115
See? It's a ship.

01:16:32.755 --> 01:16:35.554
But it's got
the flag of England.

01:16:37.726 --> 01:16:40.389
And then I put
a pirate flag there.

01:16:40.930 --> 01:16:43.194
And if you like,
you can count

01:16:43.833 --> 01:16:45.824
how many sails there are.

01:16:46.535 --> 01:16:48.367
You want to try that?

01:16:53.776 --> 01:16:55.005
Fifteen.

01:16:55.277 --> 01:16:56.609
That's right.

01:16:57.279 --> 01:16:58.611
Fifteen.

01:17:00.082 --> 01:17:02.710
No, no, it's yours.
I made it for you.

01:17:18.133 --> 01:17:20.193
If it's all right with you,

01:17:20.736 --> 01:17:23.338
I thought maybe we could sleep
in separate beds for a while,

01:17:23.339 --> 01:17:25.830
just until we get
to know each other again.

01:17:27.243 --> 01:17:29.143
I made up the spare room.

01:17:30.246 --> 01:17:31.577
All right.

01:17:40.289 --> 01:17:43.054
What do you hear
from your brother John?

01:17:46.195 --> 01:17:49.494
I thought you knew. He was
killed in Burma, in 1044.

01:17:51.700 --> 01:17:54.727
You never mentioned it
in any of your letters.

01:17:57.239 --> 01:17:59.401
There wasn't very much to say.

01:18:07.550 --> 01:18:09.575
Six years is a long time.

01:18:13.389 --> 01:18:16.586
I was lonely
and I was with a man once.

01:18:20.195 --> 01:18:22.027
He wasn't very interesting.

01:18:26.068 --> 01:18:27.559
Were you with anyone?

01:18:30.406 --> 01:18:32.238
It was a mistake.

01:18:48.724 --> 01:18:51.625
Thank you for the ship
you made for me.

01:18:54.997 --> 01:18:56.328
You're welcome.

01:18:57.299 --> 01:18:58.960
I'm glad you like it.

01:19:01.036 --> 01:19:03.504
Mother said
you were in the war.

01:19:03.505 --> 01:19:06.407
Did you fight?
Did you kill anybody?

01:19:10.245 --> 01:19:11.611
No.

01:19:15.250 --> 01:19:17.776
Good night.
Good night.

01:19:35.938 --> 01:19:37.701
No! You're it!

01:19:38.340 --> 01:19:41.105
Hello, Father.
Hello, Edward. Hello.

01:19:41.443 --> 01:19:42.610
Hello, dear.

01:19:42.611 --> 01:19:44.079
There's somebody waiting
for you in the den.

01:19:47.116 --> 01:19:48.379
General.

01:19:50.319 --> 01:19:51.684
Edward.

01:19:53.322 --> 01:19:56.781
I'm sorry to barge in on you like this.
Your wife kindly helped me to a drink.

01:19:58.827 --> 01:20:01.896
My feet, they keep
cutting off pieces of them.

01:20:01.897 --> 01:20:04.730
It's not dignified for men to
have to die from the feet up.

01:20:11.273 --> 01:20:14.106
Well, while everybody's been
feeling good about themselves,

01:20:14.343 --> 01:20:18.112
the Soviets, without firing a shot,
have taken over half the world.

01:20:18.113 --> 01:20:19.747
They're breathing
down our necks.

01:20:19.748 --> 01:20:21.774
They'll be in our backyard
before you know it.

01:20:21.984 --> 01:20:23.318
So, I've been telling
the President

01:20:23.319 --> 01:20:25.720
about the need to create a new
Foreign Intelligence Service.

01:20:25.721 --> 01:20:28.383
One that would do in peacetime
what OSS did during the war.

01:20:29.825 --> 01:20:33.094
Phillip Allen will be heading the
agency. Richard Hayes will be his exec.

01:20:33.095 --> 01:20:34.729
And you'll be taking
Division C,

01:20:34.730 --> 01:20:37.392
special operations that report
only to the Director.

01:20:37.800 --> 01:20:40.234
It would be limited
to overseas, obviously.

01:20:40.235 --> 01:20:43.967
Subversive operations,
intelligence gathering and analysis.

01:20:44.139 --> 01:20:47.371
And I'd be interested
in your thoughts about this.

01:20:47.976 --> 01:20:51.546
Particularly in your area of
expertise, counterintelligence.

01:20:51.547 --> 01:20:54.115
I'd be glad to help
in any way I can.

01:20:54.116 --> 01:20:55.283
That's all right.

01:20:55.284 --> 01:20:57.275
Edward, go outside.

01:20:59.121 --> 01:21:01.146
Excuse me, sir. Margaret!

01:21:03.225 --> 01:21:04.920
Come on, Edward.

01:21:05.060 --> 01:21:07.586
Come. Let's go outside,
all right? Daddy's busy.

01:21:10.566 --> 01:21:11.897
Thank you.

01:21:20.843 --> 01:21:24.912
I have to tell you, I have some
real problems with this whole thing,

01:21:24.913 --> 01:21:26.848
despite how much we need it.

01:21:27.783 --> 01:21:31.586
I'm concerned that too much power
will end up in the hands of too few.

01:21:31.587 --> 01:21:35.356
It's always in somebody's best interest
to promote enemies, real or imagined.

01:21:35.357 --> 01:21:40.420
I see this as America's eyes and ears. I
don't want it to become its heart and soul.

01:21:42.097 --> 01:21:44.031
So I told the President,
for this to work,

01:21:44.032 --> 01:21:46.763
there's gonna have to be some
kind of civilian oversight.

01:21:47.035 --> 01:21:48.526
Oversight?

01:21:49.271 --> 01:21:51.205
How can you have
a covert organization

01:21:51.206 --> 01:21:53.441
if you have people looking
over your shoulder?

01:21:53.442 --> 01:21:57.379
You know who gave Hitler his power?
The clerks and the bookkeepers.

01:21:57.513 --> 01:21:59.071
The civil servants.

01:21:59.948 --> 01:22:02.042
I have this one weakness.

01:22:02.551 --> 01:22:04.383
I believe in a just God.

01:22:05.387 --> 01:22:08.152
I always seem to err
on the side of democracy.

01:22:14.696 --> 01:22:17.665
This must be a nice place
to raise a family.

01:22:17.666 --> 01:22:19.498
I never made the time.

01:22:20.502 --> 01:22:22.402
I'll be dead
in less than a year.

01:22:25.340 --> 01:22:27.002
I love this country.

01:22:27.442 --> 01:22:30.276
We all do, sir. We all do.

01:22:40.022 --> 01:22:43.856
No matter what anyone tells you,
there'll be no one you can really trust.

01:22:47.863 --> 01:22:51.891
I'm afraid when all is said and
done, we're all just clerks, too.

01:23:11.987 --> 01:23:15.823
I was under the impression that
Dr. Ibanez supported a democracy.

01:23:15.824 --> 01:23:18.159
I'm afraid
he's changed his mind.

01:23:18.160 --> 01:23:20.728
The doctor's started to
believe his own propaganda.

01:23:20.729 --> 01:23:23.564
I mean, you dreamed this guy up,
Edward, helped get him elected.

01:23:23.565 --> 01:23:24.932
Those are the Soviets.

01:23:24.933 --> 01:23:27.068
International Department
of Central Committee members

01:23:27.069 --> 01:23:29.670
Trubnikov, Kushelnikov,

01:23:29.671 --> 01:23:32.740
who have become overly interested
in their natural resources,

01:23:32.741 --> 01:23:34.106
particularly coffee.

01:23:35.844 --> 01:23:38.814
Our economic interests
are being compromised,

01:23:39.181 --> 01:23:43.209
to say nothing of the dangers of
a Soviet presence so close to home.

01:23:44.620 --> 01:23:48.613
For security, Edward, we must
establish our own presence there.

01:23:49.191 --> 01:23:51.182
Wait, stop. Can you go back?

01:23:52.027 --> 01:23:53.961
Go back a little bit.

01:23:57.599 --> 01:23:59.295
Run it from there.

01:24:13.949 --> 01:24:15.783
I just thought
I saw something.

01:24:15.784 --> 01:24:18.386
I want you two to put your
heads together on this.

01:24:18.387 --> 01:24:21.822
Michael will be going down there
as an agricultural specialist

01:24:21.823 --> 01:24:24.759
with the Mayan Coffee Company.
Non-official.

01:24:25.894 --> 01:24:27.995
He'll be our eyes and ears.

01:24:27.996 --> 01:24:30.056
Congratulations.
Thank you, sir.

01:24:30.332 --> 01:24:31.766
Good luck.
Thank you.

01:24:32.734 --> 01:24:35.169
I wouldn't wear
my class ring down there.

01:24:35.170 --> 01:24:36.404
Yes, sir. Of course.

01:24:36.405 --> 01:24:40.501
I want all intelligence on this
sent directly to me and no one else.

01:24:44.246 --> 01:24:46.408
I believe that's
what you're looking for.

01:24:48.750 --> 01:24:50.275
That'll do it.

01:25:43.372 --> 01:25:47.536
Mr. Wilson? This came for you
through the Carlson cover address.

01:25:48.744 --> 01:25:50.439
There was no card.

01:26:42.697 --> 01:26:45.900
There's been a potential
compromise down south.

01:26:45.901 --> 01:26:47.232
Ulysses.

01:26:48.203 --> 01:26:50.071
We can't wait
another 24 hours.

01:26:50.072 --> 01:26:53.908
If you can guarantee that all assets are
in place and prepared to move on my order,

01:26:53.909 --> 01:26:56.070
I'm prepared to move as well.

01:27:00.382 --> 01:27:02.043
Come back to bed.

01:27:02.951 --> 01:27:04.646
What were you talking about?

01:27:04.886 --> 01:27:06.650
It's grown-up talk.

01:27:07.756 --> 01:27:09.451
I had a nightmare.

01:27:09.958 --> 01:27:11.517
Everything's fine.

01:27:14.463 --> 01:27:16.488
Could you stay with me
another minute?

01:27:21.069 --> 01:27:22.400
Try to get some sleep.

01:27:25.474 --> 01:27:26.702
Yes?

01:27:28.009 --> 01:27:31.502
We haven't got time to be sure on this.
This whole thing hinges on support.

01:27:31.746 --> 01:27:34.782
If we don't have the support,
I can't guarantee the outcome.

01:27:34.783 --> 01:27:36.751
Can you guarantee
the support?

01:27:37.986 --> 01:27:40.922
That's not a guarantee.
That's not an answer.

01:27:42.190 --> 01:27:46.025
Do what you have to do.
These men aren't ideological.

01:27:46.261 --> 01:27:49.296
Put more in their Christmas
stockings, and they'll fall into place.

01:27:49.297 --> 01:27:52.927
Call the station chief.
Get him out of bed.

01:27:53.335 --> 01:27:55.599
Margaret tells us that
you work with the CIA.

01:27:58.607 --> 01:28:00.973
My wife has
a vivid imagination.

01:28:01.343 --> 01:28:04.039
I'm a trade advisor.
A civil servant.

01:28:14.055 --> 01:28:15.546
Good night.
Good night.

01:28:23.465 --> 01:28:24.832
How dare you speak
to me that way?

01:28:24.833 --> 01:28:26.567
You are never to tell anybody
what I do.

01:28:26.568 --> 01:28:29.136
How dare you? Those people are my
friends! I don't have a lot of friends!

01:28:29.137 --> 01:28:32.339
You are never to tell anyone what it
is I do. Never. Do you understand me?

01:28:32.340 --> 01:28:34.575
What you do? What you do?
I don't know what you do!

01:28:34.576 --> 01:28:37.077
You leave at five, you're
home at ten, seven days a week.

01:28:37.078 --> 01:28:38.546
You don't say
a damn word to me!

01:28:38.547 --> 01:28:41.482
I live with a ghost!
I don't know what you do!

01:28:49.357 --> 01:28:50.689
Call back.

01:28:57.933 --> 01:29:00.493
They're ready.
Launch the operation.

01:29:01.670 --> 01:29:03.103
Say something.

01:29:03.471 --> 01:29:05.472
Say something.
I have to go now.

01:29:05.473 --> 01:29:08.375
Say something! Talk to me!
Say something!

01:29:08.376 --> 01:29:10.436
Look at me. Say something.

01:29:38.506 --> 01:29:41.965
Remember what I said. Don't
touch anything. All right?

01:29:45.347 --> 01:29:48.182
Merry Christmas, Margaret.
Edward. Merry Christmas.

01:29:48.183 --> 01:29:49.917
Is this young Edward?

01:29:49.918 --> 01:29:53.513
Would you like to come inside and meet
our very special guest this evening?

01:29:57.859 --> 01:29:59.520
Santa Claus.

01:29:59.728 --> 01:30:01.495
Would you like to meet Santa? Yeah.

01:30:01.496 --> 01:30:02.725
Come along.

01:30:03.198 --> 01:30:05.866
Toddy is wonderful with
children. Yes, she is.

01:30:05.867 --> 01:30:07.665
Come and meet Santa.

01:30:09.971 --> 01:30:12.907
Would you like a drink,
Edward? Thank you.

01:30:14.342 --> 01:30:17.073
I believe
congratulations are in order.

01:30:18.013 --> 01:30:21.540
The doctor has no more
patients because of malpractice.

01:30:24.486 --> 01:30:26.249
Gentlemen.
Edward.

01:30:30.058 --> 01:30:31.321
Phillip.

01:30:31.493 --> 01:30:32.653
Bill.

01:30:33.061 --> 01:30:34.392
Gentlemen,

01:30:35.130 --> 01:30:38.327
you can all be very proud
of what you've started.

01:30:41.803 --> 01:30:42.937
Merry Christmas.

01:30:42.938 --> 01:30:45.133
Merry Christmas, Bill.
Merry Christmas.

01:30:54.816 --> 01:30:56.807
Christmas
is full of surprises.

01:30:57.352 --> 01:30:59.343
Do you like surprises
under the tree?

01:31:00.755 --> 01:31:04.692
Well, we'll make sure
you have lots of surprises

01:31:05.193 --> 01:31:07.025
and things like that. Okay?

01:31:07.195 --> 01:31:10.030
I'm sure Mom and Dad agree
that that would be a good idea.

01:31:10.031 --> 01:31:13.067
Surprises are the best part
of Christmas, don't you think?

01:31:13.068 --> 01:31:16.196
How about games?

01:31:18.039 --> 01:31:20.372
How about ball games?

01:31:24.045 --> 01:31:26.113
Can I get you a towel?
I'm so sorry.

01:31:26.114 --> 01:31:28.115
Are you all right?

01:31:28.116 --> 01:31:29.516
All right. It's all right.

01:31:29.517 --> 01:31:31.151
Can you take me
home, please?

01:31:31.152 --> 01:31:32.953
I think we should go home.
Lower your voice.

01:31:32.954 --> 01:31:35.689
You can use our bath if you'd
like. I might have some dry clothes.

01:31:35.690 --> 01:31:38.751
Thank you. Come with me, Edward.
It's all right. Come with me.

01:31:38.960 --> 01:31:40.985
Can I help you up,
Mrs. Wilson?

01:32:42.290 --> 01:32:44.291
Did you know that
Phillip is going to be

01:32:44.292 --> 01:32:46.852
on the Mayan Coffee Company's
board of directors?

01:32:49.697 --> 01:32:52.428
Remember what I said to you
about friends.

01:33:05.146 --> 01:33:06.637
You look good, Edward.

01:33:07.515 --> 01:33:10.280
How long has it been?
Seven, eight years?

01:33:11.186 --> 01:33:13.347
A lot of water
under the bridge.

01:33:15.957 --> 01:33:18.824
Carolyn and I, we just
bought our first house.

01:33:19.427 --> 01:33:22.829
And everything's already broken.
I spend my weekends fixing things.

01:33:23.031 --> 01:33:27.468
By the time I get everything fixed,
it'll be time to sell the fucking house.

01:33:29.037 --> 01:33:32.006
Maybe you can give me
a heads-up on somebody.

01:33:37.245 --> 01:33:40.747
You're asking me to give you
FBI files on an American citizen?

01:33:40.748 --> 01:33:44.048
You know I can't do that. It's
against the law to spy on citizens.

01:33:45.520 --> 01:33:46.851
Keep it.

01:33:47.055 --> 01:33:49.217
Maybe someday
you'll change your mind.

01:34:17.152 --> 01:34:18.676
May I come in?

01:34:32.834 --> 01:34:35.326
You know, I've never
been in your office.

01:34:36.437 --> 01:34:38.235
How was the fishing?

01:34:39.107 --> 01:34:41.940
It was a bad year.
The water is too high.

01:34:43.678 --> 01:34:45.145
I understand you wanted to

01:34:45.146 --> 01:34:48.582
personally give me the
Operation Zapata list yourself.

01:34:52.687 --> 01:34:54.451
There isn't one, is there?

01:34:58.726 --> 01:35:00.594
You know it was
a silent operation.

01:35:00.595 --> 01:35:02.586
It wasn't silent enough.

01:35:07.302 --> 01:35:11.762
I've been asked by the President to
suggest who we no longer need with us.

01:35:15.343 --> 01:35:17.511
Who would you recommend,
Edward?

01:35:17.512 --> 01:35:19.708
I serve at the pleasure
of the Director, sir.

01:35:21.516 --> 01:35:23.416
I'm just a gatekeeper.

01:35:24.819 --> 01:35:28.016
And why is it that people
like us choose to serve,

01:35:28.823 --> 01:35:31.952
for nickels a day,
in a profession that makes us

01:35:32.393 --> 01:35:35.795
constantly look over our
shoulder to see who's watching us?

01:35:36.464 --> 01:35:38.262
When will you
make your decision?

01:35:41.269 --> 01:35:42.566
Decision?

01:35:46.174 --> 01:35:50.167
I serve at the discretion of the
President of the United States.

01:35:51.379 --> 01:35:54.508
I will do what I think
is best for the country.

01:36:00.989 --> 01:36:04.652
It's important that
we find out who's responsible.

01:36:08.229 --> 01:36:10.220
Good night.
Good night.

01:36:23.077 --> 01:36:27.378
At 2242, call received on Berlin
base chief's operational line.

01:36:27.548 --> 01:36:31.451
Man says he's senior officer,
KGB. Would not give name.

01:36:32.153 --> 01:36:33.814
Open up. Thanks.

01:36:39.427 --> 01:36:42.496
"KGB officer asks when
Mr. Edward Wilson is coming.

01:36:42.497 --> 01:36:45.330
"He wants to know
Mr. Edward Wilson's response. "

01:36:45.767 --> 01:36:47.928
Tell him
Mr. Edward Wilson is here,

01:36:48.269 --> 01:36:51.500
and would like to know what he
intends to provide us with in return.

01:36:57.679 --> 01:37:00.180
He says,
"In return for safe journey,

01:37:00.181 --> 01:37:03.183
"he will provide Mr. Wilson
with clear understanding

01:37:03.184 --> 01:37:06.176
"of last three losses
in Moscow

01:37:06.621 --> 01:37:10.057
"and identities of
Soviet agents in your country,

01:37:11.225 --> 01:37:13.820
"penetrations
of Moscow station.

01:37:14.829 --> 01:37:18.129
"He will also speak personally
with Mr. Edward Wilson about

01:37:19.734 --> 01:37:21.065
"Ulysses.

01:37:21.903 --> 01:37:24.269
"Things only he knows
of Ulysses,

01:37:24.405 --> 01:37:26.931
"how he thinks,
what he plans to do,

01:37:27.575 --> 01:37:31.569
"and what he wants Mr. Edward
Wilson to think he is doing.

01:37:32.613 --> 01:37:36.106
"To establish bonafides,
he will carry with him

01:37:36.250 --> 01:37:41.245
"KGB surveillance photographs
of all CIA officers in Moscow

01:37:43.057 --> 01:37:47.824
"and would be more than happy
to take polygraph. "

01:37:56.971 --> 01:37:58.234
Ulysses.

01:38:02.744 --> 01:38:04.974
Ask him what his weakness is.

01:38:19.060 --> 01:38:20.550
"The cold. "

01:38:22.797 --> 01:38:24.458
Let's get him over here.

01:38:25.166 --> 01:38:28.795
My name is
Valentin Gregorievich Mironov.

01:38:29.337 --> 01:38:32.906
My children's names are
Anatoly and Sergei.

01:38:32.907 --> 01:38:37.344
My father played the cello. I
play the violin. But you know this.

01:38:37.578 --> 01:38:41.848
I risk my life to come all the way to tell
you this, to confirm what you already know.

01:38:41.849 --> 01:38:43.750
You failed the polygraph,
Mr. Mironov.

01:38:43.751 --> 01:38:46.015
You know every Russian
fails polygraph.

01:38:47.255 --> 01:38:50.122
Your polygraph doesn't
understand the Russian soul.

01:38:54.829 --> 01:38:59.494
What more do you want? I've given
you my bonafides, the names of agents,

01:38:59.934 --> 01:39:03.336
w£o has been compromised,
who you need to know about.

01:39:04.205 --> 01:39:06.833
I want to speak to
Mr. Edward Wilson.

01:39:07.809 --> 01:39:10.377
We were told Mironov was with these
men the day the photo was taken.

01:39:10.378 --> 01:39:11.878
Your immediate superior?

01:39:11.879 --> 01:39:13.880
We're not even sure that any
of the circled men are him.

01:39:13.881 --> 01:39:16.817
I told you this three times
already. Sergei Budanov.

01:39:17.185 --> 01:39:19.619
I want to speak to
Mr. Edward Wilson.

01:39:24.325 --> 01:39:25.986
I would like some tea.

01:39:29.831 --> 01:39:31.164
There isn't any.

01:39:31.165 --> 01:39:33.327
I get thirsty
when I say too much.

01:39:33.568 --> 01:39:36.537
You going to keep up this inane
questioning for much longer?

01:39:37.839 --> 01:39:41.275
There's nothing you've told us
we don't know, Mr. Mironov.

01:39:42.510 --> 01:39:44.678
I think you better try
a little harder.

01:39:44.679 --> 01:39:48.445
I didn't come here to deal
with children, Mr. Edison.

01:39:49.050 --> 01:39:50.711
Or is it Mr. Brocco?

01:39:53.154 --> 01:39:55.145
We do our homework, too.

01:40:05.199 --> 01:40:07.759
Hello, Mr. Mironov.
I'm Mr. Wilson.

01:40:13.307 --> 01:40:14.832
Hello, Mother.

01:40:17.812 --> 01:40:22.807
Ulysses is obsessed with you. Night
and day, you are always on his mind.

01:40:23.885 --> 01:40:25.477
He trusts nobody.

01:40:25.653 --> 01:40:29.385
The only one whom he lets
close is his aide, Sasha.

01:40:30.258 --> 01:40:33.557
He is methodical, he plans
things years in advance.

01:40:34.495 --> 01:40:37.364
For instance, you should know
he has developed a friendship

01:40:37.365 --> 01:40:39.492
with a certain
neighbor of yours.

01:40:39.834 --> 01:40:43.862
Fidel Castro. A young man
he has high hopes for.

01:40:44.438 --> 01:40:48.170
I understand you had a most
interesting fish swim your way.

01:40:48.576 --> 01:40:52.245
Mr. Allen thought it might be
possible for me to speak with him.

01:40:52.246 --> 01:40:54.681
With you as the chaperone,
of course.

01:40:54.682 --> 01:40:56.983
I brought him a little gift
I'm sure he'll appreciate.

01:40:56.984 --> 01:40:59.146
Send Mironov in immediately.

01:40:59.921 --> 01:41:02.287
It'll be nice to be closely
working with you again.

01:41:02.590 --> 01:41:06.891
I expect you to show me Washington.
We can paint the town red together.

01:41:08.863 --> 01:41:11.264
Valentin Mironov,
Arch Cummings.

01:41:11.399 --> 01:41:14.401
It is a great pleasure
to meet you. My pleasure.

01:41:14.402 --> 01:41:15.502
Now, please sit down.

01:41:15.503 --> 01:41:18.836
It's nice to have someone like
you on our side of the street.

01:41:20.274 --> 01:41:22.208
I thought you may enjoy this.

01:41:22.443 --> 01:41:25.276
It's something you might appreciate.
I hope you haven't read it.

01:41:27.014 --> 01:41:28.448
Very clever.

01:41:29.984 --> 01:41:31.418
Thank you.

01:41:34.388 --> 01:41:36.721
All Russia is our orchard.

01:41:37.158 --> 01:41:39.524
The land is great
and beautiful.

01:41:39.860 --> 01:41:42.729
There are many
wonderful places in it.

01:41:42.730 --> 01:41:44.391
Think, Anya.

01:41:44.565 --> 01:41:47.033
Your grandfather,
your great-grandfather...

01:41:47.034 --> 01:41:51.301
This is a very bad translation.
It is much funnier in Russian.

01:41:54.141 --> 01:41:55.909
And now, doesn't
something human look at you

01:41:55.910 --> 01:41:58.072
from every cherry
in the orchard?

01:41:58.512 --> 01:42:00.742
From every leaf
and every stalk?

01:42:01.682 --> 01:42:04.015
Don't you hear their voices?

01:42:05.019 --> 01:42:08.387
It's awful.
Your orchard is terrible!

01:42:08.723 --> 01:42:11.591
And when in the evening or at night,
when you walk through the orchard

01:42:11.592 --> 01:42:14.027
and the old bark glows
with the dim light

01:42:14.028 --> 01:42:17.063
and the old cherry trees seem
to be dreaming of all that was

01:42:17.064 --> 01:42:19.966
a hundred, two hundred years ago, and
are repressed by their heavy visions.

01:42:19.967 --> 01:42:21.628
I'm due at a meeting.

01:42:21.936 --> 01:42:25.372
We've left those 200 years behind us,
but so far, we gained nothing at all.

01:42:25.606 --> 01:42:28.200
We don't yet know
what the past is to be to us.

01:42:28.876 --> 01:42:34.144
We only philosophize. We complain
that we are dull, or we drink vodka.

01:42:34.949 --> 01:42:38.084
For it's so clear that in order
to begin to live in the present,

01:42:38.085 --> 01:42:39.951
we must first redeem the past.

01:42:45.559 --> 01:42:47.050
Are you Laura?

01:42:47.762 --> 01:42:49.062
What?

01:42:49.063 --> 01:42:52.192
Are you Laura? I'm supposed to
offer you a ride.

01:43:15.923 --> 01:43:17.448
Hello, Edward.

01:43:18.693 --> 01:43:20.024
Hello, Laura.

01:43:21.762 --> 01:43:23.594
Why all the mystery?

01:43:27.034 --> 01:43:28.866
Do you have children?

01:43:29.036 --> 01:43:30.697
I have a boy.

01:43:31.672 --> 01:43:33.504
Edward Junior.

01:43:38.179 --> 01:43:39.840
Do you have anybody?

01:43:43.684 --> 01:43:45.084
A cat.

01:43:49.990 --> 01:43:53.722
I've often imagined what my life
would have been like with you.

01:43:55.262 --> 01:43:57.288
And what did you imagine?

01:43:58.566 --> 01:44:00.625
I thought you might teach.

01:44:01.235 --> 01:44:02.862
Probably poetry.

01:44:04.805 --> 01:44:07.570
I saw us living
in a small college town.

01:44:22.790 --> 01:44:27.557
You once said to me you were afraid your
life was already planned out for you.

01:44:31.732 --> 01:44:33.894
Are you doing
what you want to do?

01:44:36.570 --> 01:44:38.800
My life has been
full of surprises.

01:45:05.132 --> 01:45:07.192
You owe me
a day at the beach.

01:45:51.212 --> 01:45:53.043
How long do you think
you'll be?

01:45:53.681 --> 01:45:55.478
As long as it takes.

01:46:00.087 --> 01:46:02.852
I think maybe I'll go ahead. All right.

01:46:07.061 --> 01:46:10.224
Nothing else
is built the same

01:46:10.397 --> 01:46:14.033
Nothing in the world

01:46:14.034 --> 01:46:17.004
As the soft
and wavy frame...

01:46:18.372 --> 01:46:19.601
Mother?

01:46:21.976 --> 01:46:24.240
There was an envelope for you
on the desk.

01:46:26.213 --> 01:46:27.647
You look lovely.

01:46:27.648 --> 01:46:29.480
Thank you, darling.

01:47:17.531 --> 01:47:19.899
It's not enough that you
ignore me our whole life?

01:47:19.900 --> 01:47:21.534
You have to humiliate me?
Margaret, please.

01:47:21.535 --> 01:47:23.265
You disgust me!
Calm down, darling.

01:47:23.637 --> 01:47:24.798
You're disgusting!

01:47:50.664 --> 01:47:52.155
We'll start from the last.

01:47:55.035 --> 01:47:57.003
So suppose
the dame ain't right

01:47:57.004 --> 01:47:58.733
Or completely
free from flaws

01:48:25.132 --> 01:48:27.123
Mother forgot
some of her things.

01:48:39.646 --> 01:48:41.308
I'll see you at home.

01:49:40.974 --> 01:49:42.465
Are you Laura?

01:49:43.510 --> 01:49:44.877
Yes.

01:49:44.878 --> 01:49:47.040
I was asked to give you this.

01:49:59.993 --> 01:50:03.429
In an unprecedented effort
to improve U.S. -Soviet ties,

01:50:03.430 --> 01:50:06.866
Premier Khrushchev began his 1·-day
tour of the United States today.

01:50:06.867 --> 01:50:09.669
The visit will start with a
tour by President Eisenhower

01:50:09.670 --> 01:50:10.970
of our nation's capital,

01:50:10.971 --> 01:50:13.873
followed by a highly anticipated
speech at the United Nations.

01:50:13.874 --> 01:50:15.675
All right,
now set it down.

01:50:15.676 --> 01:50:18.978
Following that, the Soviet Premier
will travel across the country

01:50:18.979 --> 01:50:20.413
to more casual destinations,

01:50:20.414 --> 01:50:24.407
including America's mighty steel mills,
wheat farms, and, yes, Disneyland.

